                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-155425 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-fairy-tales tag-multiple-sclerosis tag-parenting des-fairy-tales des-multiple-sclerosis des-parenting news_keywords-fairy-tale news_keywords-multiple-sclerosis-2 news_keywords-parenting"
                                id="post-155425">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Parenting on the Dark Side</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
							</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-01-08T14:58:58+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">January 8, 2015 9:58 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">January 8, 2015 9:58 am</span><span class="postMetaHeaderCommentCount commentCount">
</span>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">SPOKANE, WASH. &#x2014; My therapist calls me a &#x201C;loyal skeptic,&#x201D; a person who struggles to gain security and certainty in a world that she believes is inherently dangerous. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That might explain my attraction, at a young age, to the old fairy tales with less-than-happy endings. It might also explain why I now write such dark tales myself, about untrustworthy characters who are surprised by
                                        their own proclivities for violence or indifference.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> What it doesn&#x2019;t explain is why I willingly became a mother, ushering young kids into an environment I find cruel and random.<span id="more-155425"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/08/opinion/0108PRIVATELIVES/0108PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject"
                                            role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/08/opinion/0108PRIVATELIVES/0108PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/01/08/opinion/0108PRIVATELIVES/0108PRIVATELIVES-blog480.jpg"
                                                    id="100000003436049" width="480" height="678" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="678">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Rebekka Dunlap</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I try to keep things lighthearted with my son, now 5, and my daughter, 2. But my influence shows.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;What&#x2019;s beyond space?&#x201D; Henry asks us one night at dinner.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;That&#x2019;s a great question,&#x201D; my husband says. &#x201C;No one really knows.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;I know,&#x201D; Henry says. &#x201C;It&#x2019;s just nothing. Just blank. Like a black piece of paper.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> At night, I read fairy tales to the kids &#x2014; &#x201C;Hansel and Gretel,&#x201D; &#x201C;Snow-White and Rose-Red&#x201D; &#x2014; stories in which unsentimental children are abandoned in a brutal world, left to
                                        fend for themselves. My son briefly develops a fear of wolves; my daughter becomes terrified of skeletons. I want to tell them: People are scarier than wolves; we all have a skeleton inside of us. But I know better
                                        than to say such things, and maybe they need to feel what they feel and fear what they fear. I hold them close and kiss their heads and tell them I&#x2019;ll always keep them safe. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> When I&#x2019;m diagnosed with multiple sclerosis, we hide it from the children. I&#x2019;m prescribed a daily shot of a drug called Copaxone, which I shoot into my body with a chunky device called an Autoject. In the
                                        evenings I take the Autoject, cotton balls, alcohol swabs, needle and sharps container into my bedroom and hide there, prepping and then icing the shot. My husband brushes the kids&#x2019; teeth, puts them into
                                        pajamas, wrestles with them for distraction. I listen to their shrieks of pleasure as I wipe my skin down, as I record the day&#x2019;s shot into a journal.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> One night I hear Henry ask, &#x201C;Where&#x2019;s Mommy?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The next second he&#x2019;s bursting into the room, just as I depress the button on the Autoject. I&#x2019;m shooting into my arm this day, and Henry&#x2019;s eyes widen as he hears the needle lurch and engage. There
                                        is a soft hissing sound as the medicine sprays into the fat of my upper arm.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;Whoa, Mom,&#x201D; he says. &#x201C;Does it hurt?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;No,&#x201D; I tell him, and it doesn&#x2019;t, not yet. The pain comes a minute or so later, as the medicine spreads. It lasts only a few minutes, and I almost enjoy it: It is a pain I can sink my teeth into,
                                        unlike the nerve pain, a constant part of M.S., which buzzes and vibrates without a clear center.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> My husband enters the room, ferrying my daughter.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> &#x201C;Isn&#x2019;t Mommy brave?&#x201D; he says. &#x201C;She does this every night. Isn&#x2019;t she strong?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Henry nods in agreement, and then, curiosity quenched, races off to play.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> It&#x2019;s dumb to hide things from them, I realize now. The shots, like the M.S., are a part of my daily life &#x2014; our daily life &#x2014; and hiding things gives them only more meaning and terror.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But soon Henry has questions: &#x201C;Does Daddy have M.S.? Will I get M.S.? Will Louise get it? Why do you have it?&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Questions that receive a firm &#x201C;no&#x201D;; questions I can&#x2019;t answer with absolute confidence; questions I have no answers to at all. I stumble through them as best as I can.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I worry about what sort of mother I&#x2019;ll be in five years, or 10. Will I be able to button their coats? Will I be able to stroke their hair, go on a hike with them, eat food in front of them without embarrassing
                                        them deeply?</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I think of the fairy tale &#x201C;The Girl Without Hands,&#x201D; in which a girl willingly allows her father to chop off her limbs in order to save him from the devil. It is not a story I will read to the children,
                                        but they might discover it one day on their own.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I note the faint intention tremor in my fingers. I learn to feel grateful for its faintness.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The beautiful thing about having a dark perspective is that you understand implicitly how everything could be far worse, and you are immediately grateful for any goodness you uncover. There are unthinkable tragedies
                                        unfolding as we speak; there are people turning on one another, there is abuse, there is starvation, there is greed and avarice. This small revolt of my own body against itself is a trivial matter, a hiccup of fate.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I gather my kids close to me at night. With a child tucked in each arm, we hunker before our books as though before a campfire, marveling at the world, a terrible place, but also a place for the brave, for those willing
                                        to love well and hard.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//sharmashields.com/">Sharma Shields</a> is the author of the forthcoming novel &#x201C;The Sasquatch Hunter&#x2019;s Almanac.&#x201D; </em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
